{
  "$schema": "https://aka.ms/codetour-schema",
  "title": "00 ‚Äî Orientation: the whole project in 5 minutes",
  "description": "Start here. This tour walks the project layout ‚Äî main.go, migrations, each internal package, and the web and CLI gateways ‚Äî before you dive into the detailed concept tours.",
  "steps": [
    {
      "file": "main.go",
      "line": 1,
      "title": "0.1 ‚Äî What Balaur is",
      "description": "Balaur compiles to **one binary**. Run it with `go run . serve` (development) or build it with `CGO_ENABLED=0 go build -o balaur .` (release). The binary:\n\n- Embeds **PocketBase** as a Go library ‚Äî a SQLite-backed data/auth engine\n- Serves the **Hearthwood HTMX web UI** from memory (no external server needed)\n- Runs **local LLM inference** through a **llamafile subprocess** in `internal/llama` ‚Äî the supervisor spawns the engine, health-probes it, and shuts it down when Balaur exits\n- Can also talk to any **OpenAI-compatible endpoint** over the same HTTP client, so `local` just means an endpoint Balaur spawns and tends itself\n\nThe binary does not contain models ‚Äî those are downloaded data files. All application code, templates, and CSS are embedded at compile time.\n\nSee `go.mod` for the dependency tree. Notice there is no web framework, no ORM, no router library ‚Äî PocketBase provides the HTTP router; Go's standard library covers the rest."
    },
    {
      "file": "main.go",
      "line": 33,
      "title": "0.2 ‚Äî main.go: thin wiring",
      "description": "```go\napp := pocketbase.New()\nmigratecmd.MustRegister(app, app.RootCmd, ...)\ncli.Register(app, app.RootCmd)        // machine-facing JSON gateway\napp.OnServe().BindFunc(func(se *core.ServeEvent) error {\n    web.Register(se)                   // Hearthwood web gateway\n    registerRecap(se.App)              // hourly summary cron\n    registerNudge(se.App)              // minute nudge cron\n    registerBriefing(se.App)           // daily briefing cron\n    registerSearchIndex(se.App)        // FTS5 sidecar boot\n    ...\n})\napp.Start()\n```\n\n`main.go` is intentionally thin ‚Äî **orchestration only**. Four concerns:\n\n1. **Create the app** ‚Äî PocketBase with default SQLite storage\n2. **Register migrations** ‚Äî the blank import `_ \"balaur/migrations\"` runs `init()` in that package, registering the schema\n3. **Register gateways** ‚Äî `cli.Register` (JSON) and `web.Register` (HTMX) both call `internal/turn` internally; they only render its events differently\n4. **Wire background jobs** ‚Äî recap, nudge, briefing, and search index all registered after serve is established\n\nEverything else lives in focused packages under `internal/`. AGENTS.md rule: *gateways adapt; they never re-implement.*"
    },
    {
      "file": "migrations/1749600000_init.go",
      "line": 10,
      "title": "0.3 ‚Äî Schema as code",
      "description": "```go\nfunc init() {\n    m.Register(InitCollections, dropCollections)\n}\n```\n\n`init()` is a special Go function that runs automatically when the package is imported ‚Äî before `main()`. Here it registers the migration with PocketBase's migration runner.\n\nThe filename prefix `1749600000` is a Unix timestamp ‚Äî migrations run in filename order (alphabetically), so the timestamp ensures correct sequence as you add more migrations later. There are currently **19 migration files** in the repo (the additional files after init add knowledge, summaries, LLM settings, tasks, trackers, extensions, boards, and more).\n\n`InitCollections` creates the foundational collections: `conversations`, `messages`, `memories`, `skills`, `heads`, `grants`, `audit_log`. All with owner-only API rules ‚Äî no anonymous or cross-user access.\n\n**Explore the schema:** open `pb_data/data.db` in any SQLite viewer after running the server once, and browse the `_collections` table."
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/llm/llm.go",
      "line": 42,
      "title": "0.4 ‚Äî Package map: internal/llm",
      "description": "Balaur's single seam to language models. Three files:\n\n- `llm.go` ‚Äî the `Client` interface and shared types (`Message`, `Chunk`, `ToolCall`, `ToolSpec`)\n- `env.go` ‚Äî reads env-var config (`BALAUR_CHAT_MODEL`, default model URL/path)\n- `openai.go` ‚Äî the one concrete client: talks to any OpenAI-compatible HTTP endpoint (local or remote)\n\nThere is no in-process inference library. Local inference is served by a **llamafile subprocess** in `internal/llama`, reached through the same `OpenAIClient` the remote providers use. The `Embed` method exists on the interface for future use; today only the chat path is exercised.\n\nEverything above this package is provider-agnostic. The `Loop` in `internal/agent` holds a `llm.Client` and never knows which implementation is running.\n\n**Tour 01** covers this package in depth."
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/llama/supervisor.go",
      "line": 37,
      "title": "0.5 ‚Äî Package map: internal/llama",
      "description": "The llamafile subprocess supervisor. One file: `supervisor.go`.\n\n`Supervisor` owns at most one running llamafile process for the whole binary:\n\n- `EnsureServer` spawns the engine, health-probes `/health`, and returns the OpenAI base URL\n- `Stop` sends SIGKILL to the process group ‚Äî called from `main.go`'s `OnTerminate` hook\n- `LocalClient` wraps `Supervisor` behind the `llm.Client` interface: it lazily calls `EnsureServer` on first chat, then delegates every `ChatStream` and `Embed` call to an `OpenAIClient` pointed at the running engine\n\nBoth fat llamafiles (`.llamafile` ‚Äî engine + weights in one file, run via `/bin/sh`) and bare GGUFs (separate engine binary + `-m` flag) are supported.\n\n**Tour 02** covers the goroutine and channel patterns used here."
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/agent/agent.go",
      "line": 71,
      "title": "0.6 ‚Äî Package map: internal/agent",
      "description": "The conversation loop: `messages ‚Üí model ‚Üí tool calls ‚Üí tool results ‚Üí model ‚Ä¶` until the model answers in plain text.\n\n- `agent.go` ‚Äî `Loop.Run()`, the orchestrator\n- `agent_test.go` ‚Äî 4 tests with a `fakeClient`, no real model needed\n\nThe loop has no knowledge of PocketBase, HTTP, or the UI. It takes a `llm.Client`, a list of `Tool`s, and an `emit func(Event)` callback ‚Äî then drives the conversation. The caller decides what to do with events (stream HTML fragments, append to a slice, write to a database).\n\nEvent kinds: `text`, `reasoning`, `tool_start`, `tool_result`, `done`, `error`.\n\n**Tour 03** covers the loop step by step.\n**Tour 04** covers the tests."
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/heads/heads.go",
      "line": 1,
      "title": "0.7 ‚Äî Package map: internal/heads",
      "description": "Sub-agent identity and the security boundary.\n\n- `heads.go` ‚Äî `Spawn`, `Resolve`, `Merge`, `Revoke`: the lifecycle of a head (sub-agent)\n- `scoped.go` ‚Äî `Scoped`: the **only** sanctioned data path for code acting as a head\n- `heads_test.go` ‚Äî integration tests proving access denial works and is audited\n\nThe critical invariant: Go-side PocketBase access bypasses API rules. So tool code running as a head must call `AsHead(app, head).Records(...)` ‚Äî not `app.FindRecordsByFilter(...)`. The `Scoped` type enforces this at the API level.\n\n**Tour 05** covers this in full, including running the security proof test."
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/web/web.go",
      "line": 1,
      "title": "0.8 ‚Äî Package map: internal/web",
      "description": "The **Hearthwood** HTMX UI layer ‚Äî one of two gateways over `internal/turn`.\n\n- `web.go` ‚Äî `Register()` mounts routes; `handlers` struct holds app + templates; `guardLocalUI` is the DNS-rebinding + CSRF defence\n- `chat.go` ‚Äî `POST /ui/chat`: streams HTML fragments back over chunked response\n- `cards.go` ‚Äî `GET /ui/cards/{type}`: typed card registry endpoint (10 card types)\n- `boards.go` ‚Äî `GET /boards/{id}`: owner-composed dashboards of typed cards\n- `tasks.go` ‚Äî `questGroup`, the quest-log rail, OOB nudge and quest swaps\n- `knowledge.go`, `life.go`, `recap.go`, `day.go`, `journal.go`, `headsmgmt.go`, `profile.go`, `models.go` ‚Äî domain pages\n\nThe `web/` directory at the root holds the embedded assets:\n- `web/static/basm.css` ‚Äî the canonical Hearthwood design token source\n- `web/static/htmx.min.js` ‚Äî vendored, no CDN at runtime\n- `web/static/board.js` ‚Äî drag/resize/pack for boards\n- `web/templates/` ‚Äî all html/template files\n- `web/embed.go` ‚Äî exposes the `embed.FS` so the binary includes them\n\n**Tour 07** covers the Hearthwood gateway in depth.\n**Tour 08** covers the typed card/board stack."
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/cli/cli.go",
      "line": 1,
      "title": "0.9 ‚Äî Package map: internal/cli",
      "description": "The machine-facing JSON gateway ‚Äî the second surface over `internal/turn`.\n\nEvery command prints one JSON envelope on stdout:\n```json\n{\"v\":1,\"kind\":\"<command>.<subcommand>\",\"data\":{‚Ä¶}}\n```\n\n`v` is the CLI API version (integer; bumped only on breaking change). `kind` is `<command>` or `<command>.<subcommand>`. `data` is whatever the command emits. Additive fields inside `data` are free; renames or removals bump `v`.\n\nCommands: `chat`, `task`, `memory`, `skill`, `life`, `journal`, `day`, `recap`, `history`, `audit`, `verify`, `model`, `self`, `ext`, `doctor`.\n\n`balaur doctor` preflights the box with no model calls: data dir writable, core collections present, model readiness (non-fatal), OS-access gate state, extension count.\n\n**Tour 10** covers the CLI API in detail."
    }
  ]
}
